{{Infobox person | name = Mustafa Ejubović | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = 1651 | birth_place = [[Mostar]], [[Bosnia Eyalet]], [[Ottoman Empire]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1707|7|16|1651|01|01|df=y}} | death_place = Mostar, Bosnia Eyalet, Ottoman Empire | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | occupation = Historian }}
'''Mustafa Ejubović''' (1651 – 16 July 1707), also known as '''Šejh Jujo''', was a historian, writer and [[Mufti]] of [[Ottoman Bosnia and Herzegovina]].
==Biography== Mustafa Ejubović was born into a family of ethnic [[Bosniaks]] in the [[Herzegovina|Herzegovinian]] town of [[Mostar]] in 1651. His father Jusuf was a distinguished professor. Young Mustafa taught [[maktab]] and [[madrasa]] in Mostar before departing for [[Constantinople]] to study in 1677.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K4viAAAAMAAJ&q=MUSTAFA+EJUBOVI%C4%86&dq=MUSTAFA+EJUBOVI%C4%86&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQ-8j98PrNAhUFw4MKHXLuBvA4ChDoAQghMAE|title=Bašagićeva kolekcija orijentalnih rukopisa u Univerzitetskoj knjižnici u Bratislavi i njen značaj za opću i kulturnu historiju Bosne i Hercegovine|publisher=Arhiv Hercegovine|year=1998|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> There he listened to lectures on philosophy, astronomy and mathematics. When he graduated, he got a professorship at a lower madrasa in Constantinople, became famous for his lectures, and soon began to teach.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s_nliwCpBjMC&pg=PA99&dq=MUSTAFA+EJUBOVI%C4%86&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiK2rC45_rNAhUI74MKHZ_XDT4Q6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q=MUSTAFA%20EJUBOVI%C4%86&f=false|title=Bosnia the Good: Tolerance and Tradition|publisher=|date=|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> Ejubović wrote 27 [[treatise]]s on logic during his lifetime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Cvk6oMf9R7AC&pg=PA103&dq=MUSTAFA+EJUBOVI%C4%86&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQ-8j98PrNAhUFw4MKHXLuBvA4ChDoAQgbMAA#v=onepage&q=MUSTAFA%20EJUBOVI%C4%86&f=false|title=Bosnia: A Short History|publisher=|date=|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> In addition to his native [[Bosnian language]], he also spoke Arabic, Turkish and Persian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-HRpAAAAMAAJ&q=MUSTAFA+EJUBOVI%C4%86&dq=MUSTAFA+EJUBOVI%C4%86&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQ-8j98PrNAhUFw4MKHXLuBvA4ChDoAQhHMAY|title=Devetnaest stoljeća Bosne: historija i kultura Bosne od 6. do 1900. godine|publisher=Dinex|year=1998|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref>
Upon his return to Bosnia, Ejubović became the [[Mufti]] of Mostar in 1692.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2PUs9jHIGwMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=From+Codicology+to+Technology:+Islamic+Manuscripts+and+Their+Place+in&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwis2Pa79PrNAhWI6IMKHX84AvUQ6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=Ejubovic&f=false|title=From Codicology to Technology: Islamic Manuscripts and Their Place in Scholarship|publisher=Frank & Timme GmbH|year=2009|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref>
Ejubović died on 16 July 1707 in the city where he grew up, Mostar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ECqTDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA39&dq=MUSTAFA+EJUBOVI%C4%86&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiK2rC45_rNAhUI74MKHZ_XDT4Q6AEIIDAB#v=onepage&q=MUSTAFA%20EJUBOVI%C4%86&f=false|title=A Muslim Reformist in Communist Yugoslavia: The Life and Thought of Husein Đozo|publisher=|date=|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref>
