'''William Macbride Childs''' (1869–1939) was an [[England|English]] academic administrator and historian, who was involved in the foundation of the [[University of Reading]] and who served briefly as its first [[Chancellor (education)|vice-chancellor]].<ref name=willchild>{{cite web | url = http://www.reading.ac.uk/bulletin/pdfs/447.pdf | format=PDF | title = University of Reading Bulletin (16 March 2006) | publisher = University of Reading | pages = 4 | accessdate = 2010-02-10 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080308143129/http://www.reading.ac.uk/bulletin/pdfs/447.pdf | archivedate = 2008-03-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.readinglibraries.org.uk/services/local/alternatives.htm | title = Other Great People of Reading | publisher = Reading Borough Libraries | accessdate = 2010-02-04}}</ref>
==Biography== Childs was born, on 3 January 1869, in the village of [[Carrington, Lincolnshire|Carrington]], situated some {{convert|8|mi}} north of [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]] in [[Lincolnshire]]. He was the son of the Revd William Linington Childs, vicar of Carrington, and his second wife, Henrietta Fowles Bell. He had no brothers or sisters, but had a stepbrother and two stepsisters by his father's first marriage. He attended [[Portsmouth Grammar School]] and graduated from [[Keble College, Oxford|Keble College]] of the [[University of Oxford]] in 1891.<ref name=odonb>{{cite web | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/32402 | title = Childs, William Macbride (1869–1939), educationist | work = Oxford Dictionary of National Biography | publisher = Oxford University Press | first = T.A.B. | last = Corley | accessdate = 2010-02-08}}</ref>
In 1892 Childs served briefly as a secretary to [[Sir Arthur Dyke Acland, 13th Baronet|Sir Arthur Dyke Acland]], who at the time was [[Secretary of State for Education and Skills|Vice-President of the Committee on Education]], the [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|cabinet]] post that then supervised [[education in the United Kingdom]]. In 1893 he became a [[lecturer]] in history at the [[University College, Reading|University College]] in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]], being promoted to vice-principal in 1900.<ref name=odonb/>
In 1903 Childs succeeded [[Halford Mackinder]] as principal of the college. He made it his aim to turn the college into a University, working to this end by attracting students from a distance with hostels and, eventually, halls of residence. He also raised funds from prominent local residents, including [[George William Palmer (England)|George William Palmer]] and [[Alfred Palmer]], both proprietors of [[Huntley & Palmers]], and Harriet Loyd-Lindsay, wife of [[Robert Loyd-Lindsay, 1st Baron Wantage|Robert, 1st Baron Wantage]]. His first application for a charter, in 1920, was turned down, but a second application, in 1925, succeeded. In 1926, when the [[University of Reading]] officially received that charter, Childs became the first vice-chancellor, being born aloft by his students and carried around the grounds.<ref name=willchild/><ref name=odonb/>
Childs retired at the age of 60, in 1929. He died on 21 June 1939 at his home at [[Hermitage, Berkshire|Hermitage]] in [[Berkshire]]. Childs Hall, a hall of residence on the University of Reading's [[Whiteknights Park]] campus, is named in honour of William Macbride Childs.<ref name=willchild/><ref name=odonb/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.reading.ac.uk/nmsruntime/saveasdialog.aspx?lID=42482&sID=102830 | format = PDF |title = Childs Hall Student Handbook | publisher = University of Reading | accessdate = 2010-02-10 }}</ref>
